# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1-octanol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Butadiene undergoes chemical degradation in the atmosphere, but it can nevertheless be found in low levels in the air of urban and suburban areas due to emission by motor vehicles.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The name butadiene can also refer to the isomer, 1,2-butadiene, which is a cumulated diene with structure H2C=C=CH−CH3.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] This allene has no industrial significance.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Caventou isolated butadiene from the pyrolysis of amyl alcohol.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] This hydrocarbon was identified as butadiene in 1886, after Henry Edward Armstrong isolated it from among the pyrolysis products of petroleum.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] In 1910, the Russian chemist Sergei Lebedev polymerized butadiene and obtained a material with rubber-like properties.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] This polymer was, however, found to be too soft to replace natural rubber in many applications, notably automobile tires.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The butadiene industry originated in the years before World War II.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Many of the belligerent nations realized that in the event of war, they could be cut off from rubber plantations controlled by the British Empire, and sought to reduce their dependence on natural rubber.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] In 1929, Eduard Tschunker and Walter Bock, working for IG Farben in Germany, made a copolymer of styrene and butadiene that could be used in automobile tires.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Worldwide production quickly ensued, with butadiene being produced from grain alcohol in the Soviet Union and the United States, and from coal-derived acetylene in Germany.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] In 2020, 14.2 million tons were estimated to have been produced.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] In the United States, western Europe, and Japan, butadiene is produced as a byproduct of the steam cracking process used to produce ethylene and other alkenes.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] When mixed with steam and briefly heated to very high temperatures (often over 900 °C), aliphatic hydrocarbons give up hydrogen to produce a complex mixture of unsaturated hydrocarbons, including butadiene.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The quantity of butadiene produced depends on the hydrocarbons used as feed.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Light feeds, such as ethane, give primarily ethylene when cracked, but heavier feeds favor the formation of heavier olefins, butadiene, and aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Butadiene is typically isolated from the other four-carbon hydrocarbons produced in steam cracking by extractive distillation using a polar aprotic solvent such as acetonitrile, *N*-methyl-2-pyrrolidone, furfural, or dimethylformamide, from which it is then stripped by distillation.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Butadiene can also be produced by the catalytic dehydrogenation of normal butane (*n*-butane).
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The first such post-war commercial plant, producing 65,000 tons per year of butadiene, began operations in 1957 in Houston, Texas.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Prior to that, in the 1940s the Rubber Reserve Company, a part of the United States government, constructed several plants in Borger, Texas, Toledo, Ohio, and El Segundo, California, to produce synthetic rubber for the war effort as part of the United States Synthetic Rubber Program.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Total capacity was 68 KMTA (Kilo Metric Tons per Annum).
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Today, butadiene from *n*-butane is commercially produced using the Houdry Catadiene process, which was developed during World War II.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] This entails treating butane over alumina and chromia at high temperatures.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] In other parts of the world, including South America, Eastern Europe, China, and India, butadiene is also produced from ethanol.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] While not competitive with steam cracking for producing large volumes of butadiene, lower capital costs make production from ethanol a viable option for smaller-capacity plants.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] This process was the basis for the Soviet Union's synthetic rubber industry during and after World War II, and it remained in limited use in Russia and other parts of eastern Europe until the end of the 1970s.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] At the same time this type of manufacture was canceled in Brazil.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] As of 2017, no butadiene was produced industrially from ethanol.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] This process was one of the three used in the United States to produce "government rubber" during World War II, although it is less economical than the butane or butene routes for the large volumes.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Still, three plants with a total capacity of 200,000 tons per year were constructed in the U.S.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] (Institute, West Virginia, Louisville, Kentucky, and Kobuta, Pennsylvania) with start-ups completed in 1943, the Louisville plant initially created butadiene from acetylene generated by an associated calcium carbide plant.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The process remains in use today in China and India.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] 1,3-Butadiene can also be produced by catalytic dehydrogenation of normal butenes.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Synthetic Rubber Program (USSRP) during World War II.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The process was much more economical than the alcohol or n-butane route but competed with aviation gasoline for available butene molecules (butenes were plentiful thanks to catalytic cracking).
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The USSRP constructed several plants in Baton Rouge and Lake Charles, Louisiana; Houston, Baytown, and Port Neches, Texas; and Torrance, California.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] In the 1960s, a Houston company known as "Petro-Tex" patented a process to produce butadiene from normal butenes by oxidative dehydrogenation using a proprietary catalyst.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] It is unclear if this technology is practiced commercially.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] After World War II, the production from butenes became the major type of production in USSR.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] 1,3-Butadiene is inconvenient for laboratory use because it is gas.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Laboratory procedures have been optimized for its generation from nongaseous precursors.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] It can be produced by the retro-Diels-Alder reaction of cyclohexene.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Sulfolene is a convenient solid storable source for 1,3-butadiene in the laboratory.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] It releases the diene and sulfur dioxide upon heating.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Most butadiene (75% of the manufactured 1,3-butadiene) is used to make synthetic rubbers for the manufacture of tires and components of many consumer items.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The conversion of butadiene to synthetic rubbers is called polymerization, a process by which small molecules (monomers) are linked to make large ones (polymers).
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The mere polymerization of butadiene gives polybutadiene, which is a very soft, almost liquid material.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The polymerization of butadiene *and* other monomers gives copolymers, which are more valued.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The polymerization of butadiene and styrene and/or acrylonitrile, such as acrylonitrile butadiene styrene (ABS), nitrile-butadiene (NBR), styrene-butadiene (SBR) and polybutadiene acrylonitrile (PBAN).
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] These copolymers are tough and/or elastic depending on the ratio of the monomers used in their preparation.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] SBR is the material most commonly used for the production of automobile tires.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Precursors to still other synthetic rubbers are prepared from butadiene.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Butadiene-based polymers, particularly polybutadiene acrylonitrile (PBAN) and hydroxyl-terminated polybutadiene (HTPB) are used as binders for ammonium perchlorate composite propellant (APCP) solid rocket motors.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Large American solid rocket motors such as those used on Titan III, Space Shuttle and Space Launch System have used PBAN, while some other nations (such as Japan in M-5 rocket and India in PSLV) use HTPB.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Amateur rocketeers often use HTPB for its reduced curing temperature and fumes, despite much higher cost.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Smaller amounts of butadiene are used to make adiponitrile, a precursor to some nylons.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The conversion of butadiene to adiponitrile entails the addition of hydrogen cyanide to each of the double bonds in butadiene.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Butadiene is used to make the solvent sulfolane.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Butadiene is also useful in the synthesis of cycloalkanes and cycloalkenes, as it reacts with double and triple carbon-carbon bonds through Diels-Alder reactions.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The most widely used such reactions involve reactions of butadiene with one or two other molecules of butadiene, i.e., dimerization and trimerization respectively.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Via dimerization butadiene is converted to 4-vinylcyclohexene and cyclooctadiene.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] In fact, vinylcyclohexene is a common impurity that accumulates when butadiene is stored.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Via trimerization, butadiene is converted to cyclododecatriene.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Some of these processes employ nickel- or titanium-containing catalysts.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Butadiene is also a precursor to 1-octene via palladium-catalyzed telomerization with methanol.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] This reaction produces 1-methoxy-2,7-octadiene as an intermediate.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The most stable conformer of 1,3-butadiene is the *s*-*trans* conformation, in which the molecule is planar, with the two pairs of double bonds facing opposite directions.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] This conformation is most stable because orbital overlap between double bonds is maximized, allowing for maximum conjugation, while steric effects are minimized.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Conventionally, the *s-trans* conformation is considered to have a C2-C3 dihedral angle of 180°.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] In contrast, the *s*-*cis* conformation, in which the dihedral angle is 0°, with the pair of double bonds facing the same direction is approximately 16.5 kJ/mol (3.9 kcal/mol) higher in energy, due to steric hindrance.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] This geometry is a local energy maximum, so in contrast to the *s-trans* geometry, it is not a conformer.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The *gauche* geometry, in which the double bonds of the *s-cis* geometry are twisted to give a dihedral angle of around 38°, is a second conformer that is around 12.0 kJ/mol (2.9 kcal/mol) higher in energy than the *s-trans* conformer.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Overall, there is a barrier of 24.8 kJ/mol (5.9 kcal/mol) for isomerization between the two conformers.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] This increased rotational barrier and strong overall preference for a near-planar geometry is evidence for a delocalized π system and a small degree of partial double bond character in the C–C single bond, in accord with resonance theory.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Despite the high energy of the *s-cis* conformation, 1,3-butadiene needs to assume this conformation (or one very similar) before it can participate as the four-electron component in concerted cycloaddition reactions like the Diels-Alder reaction.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Similarly, a combined experimental and computational study has found that the double bond of *s-trans-*butadiene has a length of 133.8 pm, while that for ethylene has a length of 133.0 pm.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] This was taken as evidence of a π-bond weakened and lengthened by delocalization, as depicted by the resonance structures shown below.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] A qualitative picture of the molecular orbitals of 1,3-butadiene is readily obtained by applying Hückel theory.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] 1,3-Butadiene is also thermodynamically stabilized.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] While a monosubstituted double bond releases about 30.3 kcal/mol of heat upon hydrogenation, 1,3-butadiene releases slightly less (57.1 kcal/mol) than twice this energy (60.6 kcal/mol), expected for two isolated double bonds.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] That implies a stabilization energy of 3.5 kcal/mol.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Similarly, the hydrogenation of the terminal double bond of 1,4-pentadiene releases 30.1 kcal/mol of heat, while hydrogenation of the terminal double bond of conjugated (*E*)-1,3-pentadiene releases only 26.5 kcal/mol, implying a very similar value of 3.6 kcal/mol for the stabilization energy.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The ~3.5 kcal/mol difference in these heats of hydrogenation can be taken to be the resonance energy of a conjugated diene.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The industrial uses illustrate the tendency of butadiene to polymerize.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Its susceptibility to 1,4-addition reactions is illustrated by its hydrocyanation.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Like many dienes, it undergoes Pd-catalyzed reactions that proceed via allyl complexes.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] It is a partner in Diels–Alder reactions, e.g. with maleic anhydride to give tetrahydrophthalic anhydride.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Like other dienes, butadiene is a ligand for low-valent metal complexes, e.g. the derivatives Fe(butadiene)(CO)3 and Mo(butadiene)3.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] LC50 is 12.5–11.5 vol% for inhalation by rats and mice.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Long-term exposure has been associated with cardiovascular disease.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] There is a consistent association with leukemia, as well as a significant association with other cancers.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] IARC has designated 1,3-butadiene as a Group 1 carcinogen ('carcinogenic to humans'), and the Agency for Toxic Substances Disease Registry and the US EPA also list the chemical as a carcinogen.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The American Conference of Governmental Industrial Hygienists (ACGIH) lists the chemical as a suspected carcinogen.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] The Natural Resources Defense Council (NRDC) lists some disease clusters that are suspected to be associated with this chemical.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] 1,3-Butadiene is also a suspected human teratogen.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Prolonged and excessive exposure can affect many areas in the human body; blood, brain, eye, heart, kidney, lung, nose and throat have all been shown to react to the presence of excessive 1,3-butadiene.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] Animal data suggest that women have a higher sensitivity to possible carcinogenic effects of butadiene over men when exposed to the chemical.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] This may be due to estrogen receptor impacts.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] While these data reveal important implications to the risks of human exposure to butadiene, more data are necessary to draw conclusive risk assessments.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] There is also a lack of human data for the effects of butadiene on reproductive and development shown to occur in mice, but animal studies have shown breathing butadiene during pregnancy can increase the number of birth defects, and humans have the same hormone systems as animals.
[src:1-octanol/1-3-butadiene] 1,3-Butadiene is recognized as a highly reactive volatile organic compound (HRVOC) for its potential to readily form ozone, and as such, emissions of the chemical are highly regulated by TCEQ in parts of the Houston-Brazoria-Galveston Ozone Non-Attainment Area.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] In one industrial chemical synthesis, acetylene reacts with two equivalents of formaldehyde to form butyne-1,4-diol.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] Hydrogenation of butyne-1,4-diol gives butane-1,4-diol.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] It is also made on an industrial scale from maleic anhydride in the Davy process, which is first converted to the methyl maleate ester, then hydrogenated.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] Other routes are from butadiene, allyl acetate and succinic acid.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] A biological route to BD has been commercialized that uses a genetically modified organism.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] The biosynthesis proceeds via 4-hydroxybutyrate.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is used industrially as a solvent and in the manufacture of some types of plastics, elastic fibers and polyurethanes.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] In organic chemistry, 1,4-butanediol is used for the synthesis of γ-butyrolactone (GBL).
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] In the presence of phosphoric acid and high temperature, it dehydrates to the important solvent tetrahydrofuran.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] At about 200 °C in the presence of soluble ruthenium catalysts, the diol undergoes dehydrogenation to form butyrolactone.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] It is used to synthesize 1,4-butanediol diglycidyl ether which is then used as a reactive diluent for epoxy resins.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] 1,4-Butanediol is used in the production of polybutylene terephthalate (PBT) plastic.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] World production of butane-1,4-diol was claimed to be about one million metric tons per year and market price is about US$2,000 (€1,600) per ton in 2005.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] In 2013, worldwide production was claimed to be billions of pounds (consistent with approximately one million metric tons).
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] Almost half of it is dehydrated to tetrahydrofuran to make fibers such as Spandex.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is also used as a recreational drug known by some users as "Bute", "One Comma Four", "Liquid Fantasy", "One Four Bee" or "One Four B-D-O".
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] Some federal courts in the United States have stated that 1,4-butanediol exerts effects similar to its metabolite, GABA analogue gamma-hydroxybutyrate (GHB), but several other federal courts have ruled that it does not.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] 1,4-but***e***nediol (CAS 110-64-5) may be incorrectly sold as 1,4-butanediol but should not be confused with it.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is rapidly converted into GHB acid by the enzymes alcohol dehydrogenase and aldehyde dehydrogenase, and differing levels of these enzymes may account for differences in effects and side effects between users.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] While co-administration of ethanol and GHB already poses serious risks, co-administration of ethanol with 1,4-butanediol will interact considerably and has many other potential risks.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] This is because the same enzymes that are responsible for metabolizing alcohol also metabolize 1,4-butanediol so there is a strong chance of a dangerous drug interaction.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol seems to have two types of pharmacological actions.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] The major psychoactive effects of 1,4-butanediol are because it is metabolized into GHB; however there is a study suggesting that 1,4-butanediol may have potential alcohol-like pharmacological effects on its own.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] The study arrived at this conclusion based on the finding that butane-1,4-diol coadministered with ethanol led to potentiation of some of the behavioral effects of ethanol.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] However, potentiation of ethanol's effects may simply be caused by competition for the alcohol dehydrogenase and aldehyde dehydrogenase enzymes with co-administered 1,4-butanediol.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] The shared metabolic rate-limiting steps thus leads to slowed metabolism and clearance for both compounds including ethanol's known toxic metabolite acetaldehyde.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] Another study found no effect following intracerebroventricular injection of butane-1,4-diol in rats.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] This contradicts the hypothesis of butane-1,4-diol having inherent alcohol-like pharmacological effects.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] Like gamma-hydroxybutyric acid, butane-1,4-diol is safe only in small amounts.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] Adverse effects in higher doses include nausea, vomiting, dizziness, sedation, vertigo, and potentially death if ingested in large amounts.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] Anxiolytic effects are diminished and side effects increased when used in combination with alcohol.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] While butane-1,4-diol is not currently scheduled federally in the United States, a number of states have classified 1,4-butanediol as a controlled substance.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] Individuals have been prosecuted for possession of 1,4-butanediol under the Federal Analog Act as substantially similar to GHB.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] A federal case in New York in 2002 ruled that 1,4-butanediol could not be considered an analog of GHB under federal law, but that decision was later overturned by the Second Circuit.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] A jury in Federal District Court in Chicago found that 1,4-butanediol was not an analog of GHB under federal law, which was not disputed on the case's appeal to the Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals, however this finding did not affect the outcome of the case.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] In the United Kingdom, 1,4-butanediol was scheduled in December 2009 (along with another GHB precursor, gamma-butyrolactone) as a Class C controlled substance.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] In Germany, the drug is not explicitly illegal, but might also be treated as illegal if used as a drug.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] It is controlled as a Schedule VI precursor in Canada.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] A toy called "Bindeez" ("Aqua Dots" in North America) was recalled by the distributor in November 2007 because of the presence of butane-1,4-diol.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] The toy consists of small beads that stick to each other by sprinkling water.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] The production plant seems to have intended to cut costs by replacing less toxic pentane-1,5-diol with butane-1,4-diol.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] ChemNet China listed the price of butane-1,4-diol at between about US$1,350–2,800 per metric ton, while the price for 1,5-pentanediol is about US$9,700 per metric ton.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] In August 2021, several people fell severely ill after consuming drinks at building L2.01 at the Lichtwiese Campus of Darmstadt Technical University, Germany.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] Seven showed severe symptoms, two were transported to a hospital in Frankfurt am Main, and a 30-year-old person was, for a time, in a critical state.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol had been detected in milk packages, as well as in water filters.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] At the location, detectives also found bromophenols and dicyclohexylamine.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] A variety of 1,4-butanediol derivatives are GHB-like drugs or GHB receptor agonists.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] These include GHB itself, γ-butyrolactone (GBL), aceburic acid, ethyl acetoxy butanoate (EAB), Γ-crotonolactone, γ-hydroxybutyraldehyde, γ-hydroxyvaleric acid (GHV), γ-valerolactone (GVL), γ-hydroxycrotonic acid (GHC or T-HCA), and 4-hydroxy-4-methylpentanoic acid (UMB68), among others.
[src:1-octanol/1-4-butanediol] An analogue that is not a 1,4-butanediol derivative but is related and still shows affinity for the GHB receptor is 3-chloropropanoic acid (UMB66).
[src:1-octanol/1-5-pentanediol] 1,5-Pentanediol is produced by hydrogenation of glutaric acid and its derivatives.
[src:1-octanol/1-5-pentanediol] It can also be prepared by hydrogenolysis of tetrahydrofurfuryl alcohol.
[src:1-octanol/1-5-pentanediol] 1,4-Pentadiene can be prepared from 1,5-pentadiol via the diacetate.
[src:1-octanol/1-5-pentanediol] A toy called *Bindeez* (*Aqua Dots* in North America) was recalled by the distributor in November 2007 due to the unauthorized substitution of 1,5-pentanediol with 1,4-butanediol.
[src:1-octanol/1-5-pentanediol] The toy consists of small beads that stick to each other when sprinkled with water.
[src:1-octanol/1-5-pentanediol] 1,4-Butanediol, which when ingested is metabolized to gamma-hydroxybutyric acid, was detected by GC-MS.
[src:1-octanol/1-5-pentanediol] ChemNet China lists the price of 1,4-butanediol at between US$1,350–2,800/tonne, while the price for 1,5-pentanediol is about US$9,700/tonne.
[src:1-octanol/1-aminoethanol] 1-Aminoethanol exists in a solution of acetaldehyde and aqueous ammonia.
[src:1-octanol/1-aminoethanol] 1-Aminoethanol is suggested as intermediate in Strecker reaction of alanine synthesis.
[src:1-octanol/1-aminoethanol] 1-Aminoethanol was first prepared in 1833 by the German chemist Johann Wolfgang Döbereiner; its empirical formula was first determined by the German chemist Justus von Liebig in 1835.
[src:1-octanol/1-aminoethanol] The structure of 1-aminoethanol remained unproven until 1877, when the German-Italian chemist Robert Schiff showed that the structure was CH3CH(OH)NH2.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] 1-Butanol occurs naturally as a minor product of the ethanol fermentation of sugars and other saccharides and is present in many foods and drinks.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] It is also a permitted artificial flavorant in the United States, used in butter, cream, fruit, rum, whiskey, ice cream and ices, candy, baked goods, and cordials.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] It is also used in a wide range of consumer products.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] The largest use of 1-butanol is as an industrial intermediate, particularly for the manufacture of butyl acetate (itself an artificial flavorant and industrial solvent).
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] It is a petrochemical derived from propylene.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Estimated production figures for 1997 are: United States 784,000 tonnes; Western Europe 575,000 tonnes; Japan 225,000 tonnes.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Since the 1950s, most 1-butanol is produced by the hydroformylation of propene (oxo process) to preferentially form the butyraldehyde n-butanal.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Typical catalysts are based on cobalt and rhodium.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Butyraldehyde is then hydrogenated to produce butanol.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] In former times, butanol was prepared from crotonaldehyde, which can be obtained from acetaldehyde.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Butanol can also be produced by fermentation of biomass by bacteria.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Prior to the 1950s, *Clostridium acetobutylicum* was used in industrial fermentation to produce butanol.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Research in the past few decades showed results of other microorganisms that can produce butanol through fermentation.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Butanol can be produced via furan hydrogenation over Pd or Pt catalyst at high temperature and high pressure.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Constituting 85% of its use, 1-butanol is mainly used in the production of varnishes.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] It is a popular solvent, e.g. for nitrocellulose.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] A variety of butanol derivatives are used as solvents, e.g. butoxyethanol or butyl acetate.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Many plasticizers are based on butyl esters, e.g., dibutyl phthalate.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] The monomer butyl acrylate is used to produce polymers.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] 1-Butanol has been proposed as a substitute for diesel fuel and gasoline.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] It is produced in small quantities in nearly all fermentations (see fusel oil).
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Clostridium produces much higher yields of butanol.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Research is underway to increase the biobutanol yield from biomass.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Butanol is considered as a potential biofuel (butanol fuel).
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Butanol at 85 percent strength can be used in cars designed for gasoline without any change to the engine (unlike 85% ethanol), and it provides more energy for a given volume than ethanol, almost as much as gasoline.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Therefore, a vehicle using butanol would return fuel consumption more comparable to gasoline than ethanol.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Butanol can also be added to diesel fuel to reduce soot emissions.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Butan-1-ol occurs naturally as a result of carbohydrate fermentation in a number of alcoholic beverages, including beer, grape brandies, wine, and whisky.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] It has been detected in the volatiles of hops, jack fruit, heat-treated milks, musk melon, cheese, southern pea seed, and cooked rice.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] 1-Butanol is also formed during deep frying of corn oil, cottonseed oil, trilinolein, and triolein.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Butan-1-ol is one of the "fusel alcohols" (from the German for "bad liquor"), which include alcohols that have more than two carbon atoms and have significant solubility in water.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] It is a natural component of many alcoholic beverages, albeit in low and variable concentrations.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] It (along with similar fusel alcohols) is reputed to be responsible for severe hangovers, although experiments in animal models show no evidence for this.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] The acute toxicity of 1-butanol is relatively low, with oral LD50 values of 790–4,360 mg/kg (rat; comparable values for ethanol are 7,000–15,000 mg/kg).
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] It is metabolized completely in vertebrates in a manner similar to ethanol: alcohol dehydrogenase converts 1-butanol to butyraldehyde; this is then converted to butyric acid by aldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Butyric acid can be fully metabolized to carbon dioxide and water by the β-oxidation pathway.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] In the rat, only 0.03% of an oral dose of 2,000 mg/kg was excreted in the urine.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] At sub-lethal doses, 1-butanol acts as a depressant of the central nervous system, similar to ethanol: one study in rats indicated that the intoxicating potency of 1-butanol is about 6 times higher than that of ethanol, possibly because of its slower transformation by alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Liquid 1-butanol, as is common with most organic solvents, is extremely irritating to the eyes; repeated contact with the skin can also cause irritation.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] This is believed to be a generic effect of defatting.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] No skin sensitization has been observed.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] Irritation of the respiratory pathways occurs only at very high concentrations (>2,400 ppm).
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] With a flash point of 35 °C, 1-butanol presents a moderate fire hazard: it is slightly more flammable than kerosene or diesel fuel but less flammable than many other common organic solvents.
[src:1-octanol/1-butanol] The depressant effect on the central nervous system (similar to ethanol intoxication) is a potential hazard when working with 1-butanol in enclosed spaces, although the odour threshold (0.2–30 ppm) is far below the concentration which would have any neurological effect.
[src:1-octanol/1-decanol] Decanol can be prepared by the hydrogenation of decanoic acid, which occurs in modest quantities in coconut oil (about 10%) and palm kernel oil (about 4%).
[src:1-octanol/1-decanol] It may also be produced synthetically via the Ziegler process.
[src:1-octanol/1-decanol] Decanol is used in the manufacture of plasticizers, lubricants, surfactants and solvents.
[src:1-octanol/1-decanol] Its ability to permeate the skin has led to it being investigated as a penetration enhancer for transdermal drug delivery.
[src:1-octanol/1-decanol] Like other medium chain fatty alcohols, 1-decanol is able to permeate the skin which can lead to irritation.
[src:1-octanol/1-docosanol] In July 2000, docosanol was approved for medical use in the United States as an antiviral agent for reducing the duration of cold sores.
[src:1-octanol/1-docosanol] It is an over-the-counter medication (OTC).
[src:1-octanol/1-docosanol] It is sold under the brand name **Abreva** among others.
[src:1-octanol/1-docosanol] One of the most common side effects that has been reported from docosanol is headache.
[src:1-octanol/1-docosanol] Headaches caused by the medication tend to be mild and can occur in any region of the head.
[src:1-octanol/1-docosanol] In clinical trials, headache occurred in 10.4% of people treated with docosanol cream and 10.7% of people treated with placebo.
[src:1-octanol/1-docosanol] The most serious side effects, although rare, are allergic reactions.
[src:1-octanol/1-docosanol] Some of the patients experienced the symptoms of allergic reactions, including difficulty breathing, confusion, angioedema (facial swelling), fainting, dizziness, hives or chest pain.
[src:1-octanol/1-docosanol] Other side effects may include: acne, burning, dryness, itching, rash, redness, acute diarrhea, soreness, swelling.
[src:1-octanol/1-docosanol] Docosanol is thought to work by interfering with and stabilizing the host cell's surface phospholipids, preventing the fusion of the herpes virus's viral envelope with the human host cell.
[src:1-octanol/1-docosanol] This disrupted ability of the virus to fuse with the host cell membrane prevents entry and subsequent replication.
[src:1-octanol/1-docosanol] The drug was approved as a cream for oral herpes after clinical trials by the FDA in July 2000.
[src:1-octanol/1-docosanol] It was shown to shorten the healing by 17.5 hours on average (95% confidence interval: 2 to 22 hours) in a placebo-controlled trial.
[src:1-octanol/1-docosanol] Another trial showed no effect when treating the infected backs of guinea pigs.
[src:1-octanol/1-docosanol] Two experiments with 1-docosanol cream failed to show statistically significant differences by any parameter between 1-docosanol cream and vehicle control–treated sites or between 1-docosanol and untreated infection sites.
[src:1-octanol/1-octanol] Octanol is mainly produced industrially by the oligomerization of ethylene using triethylaluminium followed by oxidation of the alkylaluminium products.
[src:1-octanol/1-octanol] This route is known as the Ziegler alcohol synthesis.
[src:1-octanol/1-octanol] The process generates a range of alcohols, which can be separated by distillation.
[src:1-octanol/1-octanol] The Kuraray process defines an alternative route to 1-octanol, but using C4 + C4 building strategy.
[src:1-octanol/1-octanol] 1,3-Butadiene is dimerized concomitant with the addition of one molecule of water.
[src:1-octanol/1-octanol] This conversion is catalyzed by palladium complexes.
[src:1-octanol/1-octanol] The resulting doubly unsaturated alcohol is then hydrogenated.
[src:1-octanol/1-octanol] The distribution of a compound between water and octanol is used to calculate the partition coefficient, *P*, of that molecule (often expressed as its logarithm to the base 10, log *P*).
[src:1-octanol/1-octanol] Water/octanol partitioning is a relatively good approximation of the partitioning between the cytosol and lipid membranes of living systems.
[src:1-octanol/1-octanol] Where a and b are constants, $K_{sc/w}$ is the stratum corneum/water partition coefficient, and $K_{w/o}$ is the water/octanol partition coefficient.
[src:1-octanol/1-octanol] The values of *a* and *b* vary between papers, but Cleek & Bunge have reported the values *a* = 0, *b* = 0.74.
[src:1-octanol/1-octanol] With a flash point of 81 °C, 1-octanol is not seriously flammable, though its autoignition temperature is as low as 245 °C.
[src:1-octanol/1-octanol] 1-Octanol is mainly consumed as a precursor to perfumes.
[src:1-octanol/1-octanol] 1-Octanol hydrogen bonds to Lewis bases.
[src:1-octanol/1-octanol] It is a Lewis acid in the ECW model and its acid parameters are *EA* = 0.85 and *CA* = 0.87.
[src:1-octanol/1-octanol] Octanol has a sedative and anesthetic effect in animal studies, though 1-octanol may not be the most potent isomer.
